items.abstract:
<jats:p>Egg-laying behaviour of 15 species and 5 subspecies of the diurnal gecko genus <jats:italic>Phelsuma</jats:italic> was investigated in captivity. Specific behaviour patterns associated with egg-laying ("site cleaning", "egg patting" and defense of the clutch) are described and their significance is discussed.</jats:p>
<jats:p>This work is the first to distinguish two groups within the genus <jats:italic>Phelsuma</jats:italic> according to the m ode of oviposition: "gluers" which glue their eggs to a substrate and "non-gluers". Gluers include all species from the Mascarene Islands and <jats:italic>P. dubia</jats:italic> from Madagascar; non-gluers include species from the Seychelles, Comores and Madagascar.</jats:p>
<jats:p>The relationship between m ode of oviposition and habitat of related South African geckos together with the present-day distribution of gluing and non-gluing species of <jats:italic>Phelsuma</jats:italic> lead to certain conclusions concerning the evolution of this genus.</jats:p>
title: An investigation of egg laying in Phelsuma (Reptilia: Sauria: Gekkonidae)

At 400℃ and constant current (0.5 mA/cm<jats:sup>2</jats:sup>) the linear anodization range is limited to 2.7 V by scintillation and local oxide breakdowns. Nonporous 200 Å thick (0.4<mml:math xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mml:mi>μ</mml:mi></mml:math>F/cm<jats:sup>2</jats:sup>) oxide layers were produced at 2.0 V (400℃) and 8 V (20℃). Electron diffraction indicated a<mml:math xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mml:mi>γ</mml:mi></mml:math>-Al<jats:sub>2</jats:sub>O<jats:sub>3</jats:sub>structure at an anodization temperature of 400℃ and amorphous structure at room anodization temp. In both cases a diffusion of metal at the metal-oxide interface seems to be the main ageing mechanism.</jats:p><jats:p>The internal electrical field measured by the C-V method was unchanged in<mml:math xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mml:mi>γ</mml:mi></mml:math>-Al<jats:sub>2</jats:sub>O<jats:sub>3</jats:sub>layers during the life test.</jats:p>
